  <p>In the first week of the 2026 World Cup, Saudi Arabia's goalkeeper Mohammed Al-Owais produced the kind of performance that makes a tournament's early highlight reel — a run of saves that held Uruguay to a 1-1 draw and earned him player-of-the-match. It is the most romantic story football tells about the position: the lone figure standing between his team and defeat. It is also, viewed from the betting market, a reminder of one of the sport's least romantic facts. The goalkeeper sits at the center of a cluster of wagers — saves, penalties, cards — that integrity specialists consider the single softest target in football.</p>

  <p>This is not the headline match-fixing risk most people picture, where an entire result is bought. We covered that broader monitoring apparatus when <a href="/articles/world-cup-2026-match-fixing-integrity-monitoring-philippines.html">FIFA extended its Sportradar deal through 2031</a>. This is the more granular cousin, and in many ways the more dangerous one, because the fixable act is so small it never has to touch who wins.</p>

